,"1274–1322":"1274–1322","1185–Male":"1185–Deceased","1222–Female":"1222–Deceased","1236":"1236","1322":"1322","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","about 1235":"about 1235","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1185":"1185","about 1245":"about 1245","after 1275":"after 1275","Ormesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Ormesby Hall, Ormesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ormesby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Ormsby  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ormsby","meanings":["English: habitational name from North and South Ormsby (Lincolnshire), or either of two places called Ormesby in Norfolk and the North Yorkshire. The placenames all derive from the Old Norse personal name <i>Ormr</i> + Old Norse <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’. This surname is also common in Ireland (Connacht), where it has been established since the late 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Ormesby was born about 1245, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Ansketil de Ormesby, was 61 and her mother, Agnes Langton, was 24. She married Simon FitzSimon of Ormesby in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1275."},"et":{"about 1245–after 1275":"umbes 1245–pärast 1275","1236–Male":"1236–Surnud","1245–1275":"1245–1275","1245–1322":"1245–1322","1274–1322":"1274–1322","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1222–Female":"1222–Surnud","1236":"1236","1322":"1322","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","about 1235":"umbes 1235","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1185":"1185","about 1245":"umbes 1245","after 1275":"pärast 1275","Ormesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ormesby Hall, Ormesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1245–after 1275":"noin 1245–1275 jälkeen","1236–Male":"1236–Kuollut","1245–1275":"1245–1275","1245–1322":"1245–1322","1274–1322":"1274–1322","1185–Male":"1185–Kuollut","1222–Female":"1222–Kuollut","1236":"1236","1322":"1322","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","about 1235":"noin 1235","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1185":"1185","about 1245":"noin 1245","after 1275":"1275 jälkeen","Ormesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ormesby Hall, Ormesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1245–after 1275":"environ 1245–après 1275","1236–Male":"1236–Décédé","1245–1275":"1245–1275","1245–1322":"1245–1322","1274–1322":"1274–1322","1185–Male":"1185–Décédé","1222–Female":"1222–Décédée","1236":"1236","1322":"1322","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","about 1235":"environ 1235","1275":"1275","1274":"1274","1185":"1185","about 1245":"environ 1245","after 1275":"après 1275","Ormesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Ormesby Hall, Ormesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lin